SIMPLE: proscription
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Proscription
<hw>Pro*scrip"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>proscriptio</ets>: cf. F. <ets>proscription</ets>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of proscribing; a dooming to death or exile;
outlawry; specifically, among the ancient Romans, the public offer of a
reward for the head of a political enemy; <as>as, under the triumvirate,
many of the best Roman citizens fell by
<ex>proscription</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Every victory by either party had been followed by a sanguinary
<qex>proscription</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The state of being proscribed; denunciation;
interdiction; prohibition.</def> <rj><au>Macaulay.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Proscriptional</ent>⟦br⟧
